title: Blue Jays clinch AL East, split doubleheader with Orioles
text:
Patrick Semansky Blue Jays clinch AL East, split doubleheader with Orioles 
Toronto Blue Jays relief pitcher LaTroy Hawkins, right, celebrates with catcher Russell Martin, second from left, and teammate Chris Colabello after closing out the first baseball game of a doubleheader against the Baltimore Orioles, Wednesday, Sept. 30, 2015, in Baltimore. Toronto won 15-2 to clinch the American League East. (AP Photo/Patrick Semansky) Patrick Semansky Blue Jays clinch AL East, split doubleheader with Orioles 
Members of the Toronto Blue Jays celebrate after winning the first baseball game of a doubleheader against the Baltimore Orioles, Wednesday, Sept. 30, 2015, in Baltimore. Toronto won 15-2 to clinch the American League East. (AP Photo/Patrick Semansky) Patrick Semansky Blue Jays clinch AL East, split doubleheader with Orioles 
Toronto Blue Jays manager John Gibbons, right, celebrates with relief pitcher LaTroy Hawkins after winning the first baseball game of a doubleheader against the Baltimore Orioles, Wednesday, Sept. 30, 2015, in Baltimore. Toronto won 15-2 to clinch the American League East. (AP Photo/Patrick Semansky) Patrick Semansky Blue Jays clinch AL East, split doubleheader with Orioles 
Toronto Blue Jays' Josh Donaldson, right, celebrates with teammate Ben Revere after winning the first baseball game of a doubleheader against the Baltimore Orioles, Wednesday, Sept. 30, 2015, in Baltimore. Toronto won 15-2 to clinch the American League East. (AP Photo/Patrick Semansky) Patrick Semansky Blue Jays clinch AL East, split doubleheader with Orioles 
Toronto Blue Jays manager John Gibbons celebrates after winning the first baseball game of a doubleheader against the Baltimore Orioles, Wednesday, Sept. 30, 2015, in Baltimore. Toronto won 15-2 to clinch the American League East. (AP Photo/Patrick Semansky) Patrick Semansky Blue Jays clinch AL East, split doubleheader with Orioles 
Toronto Blue Jays' Edwin Encarnacion, center, celebrates with teammate Justin Smoak after Smoak batted him in on a home run in the ninth inning in the first baseball game of a doubleheader against the Baltimore Orioles, Wednesday, Sept. 30, 2015, in Baltimore. Toronto won 15-2 to clinch the American League East. (AP Photo/Patrick Semansky) Patrick Semansky Blue Jays clinch AL East, split doubleheader with Orioles 
Toronto Blue Jays relief pitcher LaTroy Hawkins follows through on a pitch to the Baltimore Orioles in the ninth inning in the first baseball game of a doubleheader, Wednesday, Sept. 30, 2015, in Baltimore. (AP Photo/Patrick Semansky) Patrick Semansky Blue Jays clinch AL East, split doubleheader with Orioles 
Toronto Blue Jays starting pitcher Marcus Stroman throws to the Baltimore Orioles in the eighth inning in the first baseball game of a doubleheader, Wednesday, Sept. 30, 2015, in Baltimore. (AP Photo/Patrick Semansky) Patrick Semansky Blue Jays clinch AL East, split doubleheader with Orioles 
Toronto Blue Jays' Edwin Encarnacion, center, rounds the bases past Baltimore Orioles third baseman Manny Machado, top, and relief pitcher Steve Johnson after hitting a two-run home run in the seventh inning in the first baseball game of a doubleheader, Wednesday, Sept. 30, 2015, in Baltimore. Toronto won 15-2 to clinch the American League East. (AP Photo/Patrick Semansky) Patrick Semansky Blue Jays clinch AL East, split doubleheader with Orioles 
Toronto Blue Jays starting pitcher Marcus Stroman throws to the Baltimore Orioles in the first inning in the first baseball game of a doubleheader, Wednesday, Sept. 30, 2015, in Baltimore. (AP Photo/Patrick Semansky) Blue Jays clinch AL East, split doubleheader with Orioles Associated Press | 0 comments 
BALTIMORE (AP) â€” The Toronto Blue Jays yelled, hugged and jumped for joy around the mound after clinching their first AL East title in 22 years. 
With their 15-2 rout of Baltimore in the first game of a doubleheader Wednesday, the Blue Jays brought an appropriate conclusion to their unstoppable, two-month run.
